Dawn of 1980s Italian Riflusso -- tA Trans Revolution and Its Contradictions -- tLina Pallotta’s Portrait of Porpora -- tItalian Migration And Queer Roots -- tMichela Griffo -- tWhat Does It Mean for the Italian American Community to be Trans? -- tNew Italian American Migrations: Back to Italy -- tSummer Within -- tA Queer ’Talian Pilgrimage -- tPaths for Future Exploration: Language, Situatedness, and Glocal Movements -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow does the mapping of Italian culture change when it is charted from the perspective of gender-variant people? Italian Trans Geographies tackles this question by retracing trans and gender-variant experiences within the Italian peninsula and along diasporic routes. The volume adopts a cross-disciplinary approach that combines scholarly analyses with grassroots engagement and creative work and centers the voices of Italian and Italian American transpeople through autobiographies, memoirs, interviews, poetry, and visual works. The contributions include works by key Italian trans activists, including Romina Cecconi, Porpora Marcasciano, and Helena Velena, as well as critical interpretations of scholars and artists (many of whom self-identify as trans). Ultimately, these voices show how trans people have contributed to shaping Italian places and cultures while, in turn, being shaped by those places and cultures. Through its attention to geospecific sites, the book highlights blind spots in the hegemonic Anglo-American discourse about gender and overlooked intersections between LGBTQIA+ global discourse and local realities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAmerican Studies : Italian American Studies. 4aArea Studies : Italian Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultura